# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: solidity-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] An **application binary interface** (**ABI**) is an interface exposed by software that is defined for in-process machine code access.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] Often, the exposing software is a library, and the consumer is a program.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] An ABI is at a relatively low level of abstraction.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] Interface compatibility depends on the target hardware and the software build toolchain.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] In contrast, an application programming interface (API) defines access in source code, which is a relatively high-level, hardware-independent, and human-readable format.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] An API defines an interface at the source code level, before compilation, whereas an ABI defines an interface to compiled code.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] API compatibility is generally the concern for system design and of the toolchain.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] However, a programmer may have to deal with an ABI directly when writing a program in multiple languages or when using multiple compilers for the same language.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] A complete ABI enables a program that supports an ABI to run without modification on multiple operating systems that provide the ABI.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] The target system must provide any required libraries (that implement the ABI), and there may be other prerequisites.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] ABIs include the Intel Binary Compatibility Standard (iBCS) and the System V Release 4 ABIs for various instruction sets.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] An **embedded ABI** (**EABI**), used on an embedded operating system, specifies aspects such as file formats, data types, register usage, stack frame organization, and function parameter passing of an embedded software program.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] Each compiler and assembler that supports an EABI creates object code that is compatible with code generated by other such compilers and assemblers.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] This allows developers to link libraries generated by one compiler with object code generated by another.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] Typically, an EABI is optimized for performance for the limited resources of the target embedded system.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] Therefore, an EABI may omit abstractions between kernel and user space typically found in desktop operating systems.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] The choice of EABI can affect performance.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] Widely used EABIs include the PowerPC, Arm, and MIPS EABIs.
[src:solidity-lang/application-binary-interface] Specific software implementations like the C library may impose additional limitations to form more concrete ABIs; one example is the GNU OABI and EABI for ARM, both of which are subsets of the ARM EABI.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Contracts in Solidity are similar to classes in object-oriented languages.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] They contain persistent data in state variables, and functions that can modify these variables.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Calling a function on a different contract (instance) will perform an EVM function call and thus switch the context such that state variables in the calling contract are inaccessible.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] A contract and its functions need to be called for anything to happen.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] There is no “cron” concept in Ethereum to call a function at a particular event automatically.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Contracts can be created “from outside” via Ethereum transactions or from within Solidity contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] IDEs, such as Remix, make the creation process seamless using UI elements.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] One way to create contracts programmatically on Ethereum is via the JavaScript API web3.js.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It has a function called web3.eth.Contract to facilitate contract creation.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] When a contract is created, its constructor (a function declared with the `constructor` keyword) is executed once.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Only one constructor is allowed, which means overloading is not supported.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] After the constructor has executed, the final code of the contract is stored on the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This code includes all public and external functions and all functions that are reachable from there through function calls.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The deployed code does not include the constructor code or internal functions only called from the constructor.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Internally, constructor arguments are passed ABI encoded after the code of the contract itself, but you do not have to care about this if you use `web3.js`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If a contract wants to create another contract, the source code (and the binary) of the created contract has to be known to the creator.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This means that cyclic creation dependencies are impossible.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Public state variables differ from internal ones only in that the compiler automatically generates getter functions for them, which allows other contracts to read their values.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] When used within the same contract, the external access (e.g.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] `this.x`) invokes the getter while internal access (e.g.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] `x`) gets the variable value directly from storage.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Setter functions are not generated so other contracts cannot directly modify their values.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Internal state variables can only be accessed from within the contract they are defined in and in derived contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This is the default visibility level for state variables.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Private state variables are like internal ones but they are not visible in derived contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Making something `private` or `internal` only prevents other contracts from reading or modifying the information, but it will still be visible to the whole world outside of the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Solidity knows two kinds of function calls: external ones that do create an actual EVM message call and internal ones that do not.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Furthermore, internal functions can be made inaccessible to derived contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This gives rise to four types of visibility for functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] External functions are part of the contract interface, which means they can be called from other contracts and via transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] An external function `f` cannot be called internally (i.e.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] `f()` does not work, but `this.f()` works).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Public functions are part of the contract interface and can be either called internally or via message calls.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Internal functions can only be accessed from within the current contract or contracts deriving from it.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Since they are not exposed to the outside through the contract’s ABI, they can take parameters of internal types like mappings or storage references.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Private functions are like internal ones but they are not visible in derived contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The visibility specifier is given after the type for state variables and between parameter list and return parameter list for functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] In the following example, `D`, can call `c.getData()` to retrieve the value of `data` in state storage, but is not able to call `f`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Contract `E` is derived from `C` and, thus, can call `compute`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The compiler automatically creates getter functions for all **public** state variables.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For the contract given below, the compiler will generate a function called `data` that does not take any arguments and returns a `uint`, the value of the state variable `data`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] State variables can be initialized when they are declared.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The getter functions have external visibility.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If the symbol is accessed internally (i.e. without `this.`), it evaluates to a state variable.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If it is accessed externally (i.e. with `this.`), it evaluates to a function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If you have a `public` state variable of array type, then you can only retrieve single elements of the array via the generated getter function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This mechanism exists to avoid high gas costs when returning an entire array.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] You can use arguments to specify which individual element to return, for example `myArray(0)`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Now you can use `getArray()` to retrieve the entire array, instead of `myArray(i)`, which returns a single element per call.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It generates a function of the following form.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Modifiers can be used to change the behavior of functions in a declarative way.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For example, you can use a modifier to automatically check a condition prior to executing the function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Modifiers are inheritable properties of contracts and may be overridden by derived contracts, but only if they are marked `virtual`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For details, please see Modifier Overriding.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If you want to access a modifier `m` defined in a contract `C`, you can use `C.m` to reference it without virtual lookup.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It is only possible to use modifiers defined in the current contract or its base contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Modifiers can also be defined in libraries but their use is limited to functions of the same library.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Multiple modifiers are applied to a function by specifying them in a whitespace-separated list and are evaluated in the order presented.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Modifiers cannot implicitly access or change the arguments and return values of functions they modify.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Their values can only be passed to them explicitly at the point of invocation.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] In function modifiers, it is necessary to specify when you want the function to which the modifier is applied to be run.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The placeholder statement (denoted by a single underscore character `_`) is used to denote where the body of the function being modified should be inserted.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Note that the placeholder operator is different from using underscores as leading or trailing characters in variable names, which is a stylistic choice.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Explicit returns from a modifier or function body only leave the current modifier or function body.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Return variables are assigned and control flow continues after the `_` in the preceding modifier.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] In an earlier version of Solidity, `return` statements in functions having modifiers behaved differently.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] An explicit return from a modifier with `return;` does not affect the values returned by the function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The modifier can, however, choose not to execute the function body at all and in that case the return variables are set to their default values just as if the function had an empty body.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The `_` symbol can appear in the modifier multiple times.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Each occurrence is replaced with the function body, and the function returns the return value of the final occurrence.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Arbitrary expressions are allowed for modifier arguments and in this context, all symbols visible from the function are visible in the modifier.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Symbols introduced in the modifier are not visible in the function (as they might change by overriding).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Transient storage is another data location besides memory, storage, calldata (and return-data and code) which was introduced alongside its respective opcodes `TSTORE` and `TLOAD` by EIP-1153.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This new data location behaves as a key-value store similar to storage with the main difference being that data in transient storage is not permanent, but is scoped to the current transaction only, after which it will be reset to zero.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Since the content of transient storage has very limited lifetime and size, it does not need to be stored permanently as a part of state and the associated gas costs are much lower than in case of storage.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] EVM version `cancun` or newer is required for transient storage to be available.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Transient storage variables cannot be initialized in place, i.e., they cannot be assigned to upon declaration, since the value would be cleared at the end of the creation transaction, rendering the initialization ineffective.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Transient variables will be default value initialized depending on their underlying type.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] `constant` and `immutable` variables conflict with transient storage, since their values are either inlined or directly stored in code.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Transient storage variables have completely independent address space from storage, so that the order of transient state variables does not affect the layout of storage state variables and vice-versa.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] They do need distinct names though because all state variables share the same namespace.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It is also important to note that the values in transient storage are packed in the same fashion as those in persistent storage.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] See Storage Layout for more information.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Besides that, transient variables can have visibility as well and `public` ones will have a getter function generated automatically as usual.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Note that, currently, such use of `transient` as a data location is only allowed for value type state variable declarations.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Reference types, such as arrays, mappings and structs, as well as local or parameter variables are not yet supported.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] An expected canonical use case for transient storage is cheaper reentrancy locks, which can be readily implemented with the opcodes as showcased next.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Transient storage is private to the contract that owns it, in the same way as persistent storage.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Only owning contract frames may access their transient storage, and when they do, all the frames access the same transient store.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Transient storage is part of the EVM state and is subject to the same mutability enforcements as persistent storage.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] As such, any read access to it is not `pure` and writing access is not `view`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If the `TSTORE` opcode is called within the context of a `STATICCALL`, it will result in an exception instead of performing the modification.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] `TLOAD` is allowed within the context of a `STATICCALL`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] When transient storage is used in the context of `DELEGATECALL` or `CALLCODE`, then the owning contract of the transient storage is the contract that issued `DELEGATECALL` or `CALLCODE` instruction (the caller) as with persistent storage.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] When transient storage is used in the context of `CALL` or `STATICCALL`, then the owning contract of the transient storage is the contract that is the target of the `CALL` or `STATICCALL` instruction (the callee).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] In the case of `DELEGATECALL`, since references to transient storage variables are currently not supported, it is not possible to pass those into library calls.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] In libraries, access to transient storage is only possible using inline assembly.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If a frame reverts, all writes to transient storage that took place between entry to the frame and the return are reverted, including those that took place in inner calls.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The caller of an external call may employ a `try ... catch` block to prevent reverts bubbling up from the inner calls.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Given the caveats mentioned in the specification of EIP-1153, in order to preserve the composability of your smart contract, utmost care is recommended for more advanced use cases of transient storage.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For smart contracts, composability is a very important design principle to achieve self-contained behaviour, such that multiple calls into individual smart contracts can be composed to more complex applications.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] So far the EVM largely guaranteed composable behaviour, since multiple calls into a smart contract within a complex transaction are virtually indistinguishable from multiple calls to the contract stretched over several transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] However, transient storage allows a violation of this principle, and incorrect use may lead to complex bugs that only surface when used across several calls.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If the example used memory or storage to store the multiplier, it would be fully composable.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It would not matter whether you split the sequence into separate transactions or grouped them in some way.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] You would always get the same result: after `multiplier` is set to `42`, the subsequent calls would return `42` and `84` respectively.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This enables use cases such as batching calls from multiple transactions together to reduce gas costs.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Transient storage potentially breaks such use cases since composability can no longer be taken for granted.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] In the example, if the calls are not executed in the same transaction, then `multiplier` is reset and the next calls to function `multiply` would always return `0`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This, however, can easily lead to unexpected behaviour in complex transactions, in which values set by a previous call into the contract within the same transaction remain.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The use of transient storage for reentrancy locks that are cleared at the end of the call frame into the contract, is safe.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It is recommend to generally always clear transient storage completely at the end of a call into your smart contract to avoid these kinds of issues and to simplify the analysis of the behaviour of your contract within complex transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Check the Security Considerations section of EIP-1153 for further details.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] State variables can be declared as `constant` or `immutable`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] In both cases, the variables cannot be modified after the contract has been constructed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For `constant` variables, the value has to be fixed at compile-time, while for `immutable`, it can still be assigned at construction time.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It is also possible to define `constant` variables at the file level.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Every occurrence of such a variable in the source is replaced by its underlying value and the compiler does not reserve a storage slot for it.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It cannot be assigned a slot in transient storage using the `transient` keyword either.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Compared to regular state variables, the gas costs of constant and immutable variables are much lower.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For a constant variable, the expression assigned to it is copied to all the places where it is accessed and also re-evaluated each time.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Immutable variables are evaluated once at construction time and their value is copied to all the places in the code where they are accessed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For these values, 32 bytes are reserved, even if they would fit in fewer bytes.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Due to this, constant values can sometimes be cheaper than immutable values.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Not all types for constants and immutables are implemented at this time.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The only supported types are strings (only for constants) and value types.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For `constant` variables, the value has to be a constant at compile time and it has to be assigned where the variable is declared.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Any expression that accesses storage, blockchain data (e.g.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] `block.timestamp`, `address(this).balance` or `block.number`) or execution data (`msg.value` or `gasleft()`) or makes calls to external contracts is disallowed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Expressions that might have a side-effect on memory allocation are allowed, but those that might have a side-effect on other memory objects are not.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The built-in functions `keccak256`, `sha256`, `ripemd160`, `ecrecover`, `addmod` and `mulmod` are allowed (even though, with the exception of `keccak256`, they do call external contracts).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The reason behind allowing side-effects on the memory allocator is that it should be possible to construct complex objects like e.g. lookup-tables.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Variables declared as `immutable` are a bit less restricted than those declared as `constant`: Immutable variables can be assigned a value at construction time.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The value can be changed at any time before deployment and then it becomes permanent.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] One additional restriction is that immutables can only be assigned to inside expressions for which there is no possibility of being executed after creation.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This excludes all modifier definitions and functions other than constructors.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] There are no restrictions on reading immutable variables.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The read is even allowed to happen before the variable is written to for the first time because variables in Solidity always have a well-defined initial value.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For this reason it is also allowed to never explicitly assign a value to an immutable.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] When accessing immutables at construction time, please keep the initialization order in mind.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Even if you provide an explicit initializer, some expressions may end up being evaluated before that initializer, especially when they are at a different level in inheritance hierarchy.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Before Solidity 0.8.21 initialization of immutable variables was more restrictive.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Such variables had to be initialized exactly once at construction time and could not be read before then.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The contract creation code generated by the compiler will modify the contract’s runtime code before it is returned by replacing all references to immutables with the values assigned to them.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] This is important if you are comparing the runtime code generated by the compiler with the one actually stored in the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The compiler outputs where these immutables are located in the deployed bytecode in the `immutableReferences` field of the compiler JSON standard output.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] A contract can define an arbitrary location for its storage using the `layout` specifier.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The contract’s state variables, including those inherited from base contracts, start from the specified base slot instead of the default slot zero.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] As the above example shows, the specifier uses the `layout at <base-slot-expression>` syntax and is located in the header of a contract definition.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The layout specifier can be placed either before or after the inheritance specifier, and can appear at most once.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The `base-slot-expression` must be an integer literal expression that can be evaluated at compilation time and yields a value in the range of `uint256`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The use of constants initialized using such expressions and the built-in function erc7201 is also allowed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] A custom layout cannot make contract’s storage “wrap around”.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] If the selected base slot would push the static variables past the end of storage, the compiler will issue an error.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Note that the data areas of dynamic arrays and mappings are not affected by this check because their layout is not linear.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Regardless of the base slot used, their locations are calculated in a way that always puts them within the range of `uint256` and their sizes are not known at compilation time.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] While there are no other limits placed on the base slot, it is recommended to avoid locations that are too close to the end of the address space.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Leaving too little space may complicate contract upgrades or cause problems for contracts that store additional values past their allocated space using inline assembly.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The storage layout can only be specified for the topmost contract of an inheritance tree, and affects locations of all the storage variables in all the contracts in that tree.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Variables are laid out according to the order of their definitions and the positions of their contracts in the linearized inheritance hierarchy and a custom base slot preserves their relative positions, shifting them all by the same amount.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The storage layout cannot be specified for abstract contracts, interfaces and libraries.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] Also, it is important to note that it does *not* affect transient state variables.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] For details about storage layout and the effect of the layout specifier on it see layout of storage variables.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] The identifiers `layout` and `at` are not yet reserved as keywords in the language.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p01] It is strongly recommended to avoid using them since they will become reserved in a future breaking release.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions can be defined inside and outside of contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions outside of a contract, also called “free functions”, always have implicit `internal` visibility.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Their code is included in all contracts that call them, similar to internal library functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions defined outside a contract are still always executed in the context of a contract.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] They still can call other contracts, send them Ether and destroy the contract that called them, among other things.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The main difference to functions defined inside a contract is that free functions do not have direct access to the variable `this`, storage variables and functions not in their scope.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions take typed parameters as input and may, unlike in many other languages, also return an arbitrary number of values as output.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Function parameters are declared the same way as variables, and the name of unused parameters can be omitted.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Function parameters can be used as any other local variable and they can also be assigned to.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Function return variables are declared with the same syntax after the `returns` keyword.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The names of return variables can be omitted.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Return variables can be used as any other local variable and they are initialized with their default value and have that value until they are (re-)assigned.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If you use an early `return` to leave a function that has return variables, you must provide return values together with the return statement.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] You cannot return some types from non-internal functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This restriction does not apply to library functions because of their different internal ABI.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] When a function has multiple return types, the statement `return (v0, v1, ..., vn)` can be used to return multiple values.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The number of components must be the same as the number of return variables and their types have to match, potentially after an implicit conversion.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions can be declared `view` in which case they promise not to modify the state.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If the compiler’s EVM target is Byzantium or newer (default) the opcode `STATICCALL` is used when `view` functions are called, which enforces the state to stay unmodified as part of the EVM execution.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] For library `view` functions `DELEGATECALL` is used, because there is no combined `DELEGATECALL` and `STATICCALL`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This means library `view` functions do not have run-time checks that prevent state modifications.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This should not impact security negatively because library code is usually known at compile-time and the static checker performs compile-time checks.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Calling any function not marked `view` or `pure`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Using inline assembly that contains certain opcodes.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] `constant` on functions used to be an alias to `view`, but this was dropped in version 0.5.0.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Getter methods are automatically marked `view`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Prior to version 0.5.0, the compiler did not use the `STATICCALL` opcode for `view` functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This enabled state modifications in `view` functions through the use of invalid explicit type conversions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] By using `STATICCALL` for `view` functions, modifications to the state are prevented on the level of the EVM.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions can be declared `pure` in which case they promise not to read from or modify the state.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In particular, it should be possible to evaluate a `pure` function at compile-time given only its inputs and `msg.data`, but without any knowledge of the current blockchain state.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This means that reading from `immutable` variables can be a non-pure operation.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If the compiler’s EVM target is Byzantium or newer (default) the opcode `STATICCALL` is used, which does not guarantee that the state is not read, but at least that it is not modified.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Accessing `address(this).balance` or `<address>.balance`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Accessing any of the members of `block`, `tx`, `msg` (with the exception of `msg.sig` and `msg.data`).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Pure functions are able to use the `revert()` and `require()` functions to revert potential state changes when an error occurs.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Reverting a state change is not considered a “state modification”, as only changes to the state made previously in code that did not have the `view` or `pure` restriction are reverted and that code has the option to catch the `revert` and not pass it on.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This behavior is also in line with the `STATICCALL` opcode.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It is not possible to prevent functions from reading the state at the level of the EVM, it is only possible to prevent them from writing to the state (i.e. only `view` can be enforced at the EVM level, `pure` can not).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Prior to version 0.5.0, the compiler did not use the `STATICCALL` opcode for `pure` functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This enabled state modifications in `pure` functions through the use of invalid explicit type conversions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] By using `STATICCALL` for `pure` functions, modifications to the state are prevented on the level of the EVM.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Prior to version 0.4.17 the compiler did not enforce that `pure` is not reading the state.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A contract can have at most one `receive` function, declared using `receive() external payable { ... }` (without the `function` keyword).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This function cannot have arguments, cannot return anything and must have `external` visibility and `payable` state mutability.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It can be virtual, can override and can have modifiers.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The receive function is executed on a call to the contract with empty calldata.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This is the function that is executed on plain Ether transfers (e.g. via `.send()` or `.transfer()`).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If no such function exists, but a payable fallback function exists, the fallback function will be called on a plain Ether transfer.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If neither a receive Ether nor a payable fallback function is present, the contract cannot receive Ether through a transaction that does not represent a payable function call and throws an exception.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In the worst case, the `receive` function can only rely on 2300 gas being available (for example when `send` or `transfer` is used), leaving little room to perform other operations except basic logging.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] `send()` and `transfer()` are deprecated and scheduled for removal.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] See the section on send and transfer for more information.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If you want your contract to receive Ether, you have to implement a receive Ether function (using payable fallback functions for receiving Ether is not recommended, since the fallback is invoked and would not fail for interface confusions on the part of the sender).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A contract without a receive Ether function can receive Ether as a recipient of a *coinbase transaction* (aka *miner block reward*) or as a destination of a `selfdestruct`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A contract cannot react to such Ether transfers and thus also cannot reject them.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This is a design choice of the EVM and Solidity cannot work around it.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It also means that `address(this).balance` can be higher than the sum of some manual accounting implemented in a contract (i.e. having a counter updated in the receive Ether function).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Below you can see an example of a Sink contract that uses function `receive`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A contract can have at most one `fallback` function, declared using either `fallback () external [payable]` or `fallback (bytes calldata input) external [payable] returns (bytes memory output)` (both without the `function` keyword).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This function must have `external` visibility.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A fallback function can be virtual, can override and can have modifiers.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The fallback function is executed on a call to the contract if none of the other functions match the given function signature, or if no data was supplied at all and there is no receive Ether function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The fallback function always receives data, but in order to also receive Ether it must be marked `payable`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If the version with parameters is used, `input` will contain the full data sent to the contract (equal to `msg.data`) and can return data in `output`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The returned data will not be ABI-encoded.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Instead it will be returned without modifications (not even padding).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In the worst case, if a payable fallback function is also used in place of a receive function, it can only rely on 2300 gas being available (see receive Ether function for a brief description of the implications of this).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Like any function, the fallback function can execute complex operations as long as there is enough gas passed on to it.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A `payable` fallback function is also executed for plain Ether transfers, if no receive Ether function is present.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It is recommended to always define a receive Ether function as well, if you define a payable fallback function to distinguish Ether transfers from interface confusions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A contract can have multiple functions of the same name but with different parameter types.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This process is called “overloading” and also applies to inherited functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The following example shows overloading of the function `f` in the scope of contract `A`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Overloaded functions are also present in the external interface.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It is an error if two externally visible functions differ by their Solidity types but not by their external types.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Both `f` function overloads above end up accepting the address type for the ABI although they are considered different inside Solidity.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Overloaded functions are selected by matching the function declarations in the current scope to the arguments supplied in the function call.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions are selected as overload candidates if all arguments can be implicitly converted to the expected types.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If there is not exactly one candidate, resolution fails.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Return parameters are not taken into account for overload resolution.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Calling `f(50)` would create a type error since `50` can be implicitly converted both to `uint8` and `uint256` types.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] On another hand `f(256)` would resolve to `f(uint256)` overload as `256` cannot be implicitly converted to `uint8`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Solidity events give an abstraction on top of the EVM’s logging functionality.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Applications can subscribe and listen to these events through the RPC interface of an Ethereum client.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Events can be defined at file level or as inheritable members of contracts (including interfaces and libraries).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] When you call them, they cause the arguments to be stored in the transaction’s log - a special data structure in the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] These logs are associated with the address of the contract that emitted them, are incorporated into the blockchain, and stay there as long as a block is accessible (forever as of now, but this might change in the future).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The Log and its event data are not accessible from within contracts (not even from the contract that created them).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It is possible to request a Merkle proof for logs, so if an external entity supplies a contract with such a proof, it can check that the log actually exists inside the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] You have to supply block headers because the contract can only see the last 256 block hashes.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] You can add the attribute `indexed` to up to three parameters which adds them to a special data structure known as “topics” instead of the data part of the log.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A topic can only hold a single word (32 bytes) so if you use a reference type for an indexed argument, the Keccak-256 hash of the value is stored as a topic instead.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] All parameters without the `indexed` attribute are ABI-encoded into the data part of the log.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Topics allow you to search for events, for example when filtering a sequence of blocks for certain events.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] You can also filter events by the address of the contract that emitted the event.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The hash of the signature of the event is one of the topics, except if you declared the event with the `anonymous` specifier.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This means that it is not possible to filter for specific anonymous events by name, you can only filter by the contract address.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The advantage of anonymous events is that they are cheaper to deploy and call.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It also allows you to declare four indexed arguments rather than three.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Since the transaction log only stores the event data and not the type, you have to know the type of the event, including which parameter is indexed and if the event is anonymous in order to correctly interpret the data.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In particular, it is possible to “fake” the signature of another event using an anonymous event.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Errors in Solidity provide a convenient and gas-efficient way to explain to the user why an operation failed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] They can be defined inside and outside of contracts (including interfaces and libraries).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] They have to be used together with the revert statement or the require function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In the case of `revert` statements, or `require` calls where the condition is evaluated to be false, all changes in the current call are reverted, and the error data passed back to the caller.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The example below shows custom error usage with the `revert` statement in function `transferWithRevertError`, as well as the newer approach with `require` in function `transferWithRequireError`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Errors cannot be overloaded or overridden but are inherited.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The same error can be defined in multiple places as long as the scopes are distinct.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Instances of errors can only be created using `revert` statements, or as the second argument to `require` functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The error creates data that is then passed to the caller with the revert operation to either return to the off-chain component or catch it in a try/catch statement.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Note that an error can only be caught when coming from an external call, reverts happening in internal calls or inside the same function cannot be caught.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If you do not provide any parameters, the error only needs four bytes of data and you can use NatSpec as above to further explain the reasons behind the error, which is not stored on chain.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This makes this a very cheap and convenient error-reporting feature at the same time.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] More specifically, an error instance is ABI-encoded in the same way as a function call to a function of the same name and types would be and then used as the return data in the `revert` opcode.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This means that the data consists of a 4-byte selector followed by ABI-encoded data.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The selector consists of the first four bytes of the keccak256-hash of the signature of the error type.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It is possible for a contract to revert with different errors of the same name or even with errors defined in different places that are indistinguishable by the caller.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] For the outside, i.e. the ABI, only the name of the error is relevant, not the contract or file where it is defined.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The statement `require(condition, "description");` would be equivalent to `if (!condition) revert Error("description")` if you could define `error Error(string)`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Note, however, that `Error` is a built-in type and cannot be defined in user-supplied code.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Similarly, a failing `assert` or similar conditions will revert with an error of the built-in type `Panic(uint256)`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Error data should only be used to give an indication of failure, but not as a means for control-flow.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The reason is that the revert data of inner calls is propagated back through the chain of external calls by default.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This means that an inner call can “forge” revert data that looks like it could have come from the contract that called it.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Solidity supports multiple inheritance including polymorphism.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Polymorphism means that a function call (internal and external) always executes the function of the same name (and parameter types) in the most derived contract in the inheritance hierarchy.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This has to be explicitly enabled on each function in the hierarchy using the `virtual` and `override` keywords.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] See Function Overriding for more details.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It is possible to call functions further up in the inheritance hierarchy internally by explicitly specifying the contract using `ContractName.functionName()` or using `super.functionName()` if you want to call the function one level higher up in the flattened inheritance hierarchy (see below).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] When a contract inherits from other contracts, only a single contract is created on the blockchain, and the code from all the base contracts is compiled into the created contract.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This means that all internal calls to functions of base contracts also just use internal function calls (`super.f(..)` will use JUMP and not a message call).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] State variable shadowing is considered as an error.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A derived contract can only declare a state variable `x`, if there is no visible state variable with the same name in any of its bases.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The general inheritance system is very similar to Python’s, especially concerning multiple inheritance, but there are also some differences.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Details are given in the following example.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Note that above, we call `Emittable.emitEvent()` to “forward” the emit event request.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If `Final` calls a function of `super`, it does not simply call this function on one of its base contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Rather, it calls this function on the next base contract in the final inheritance graph, so it will call `Base1.emitEvent()` (note that the final inheritance sequence is – starting with the most derived contract: Final, Base2, Base1, Emittable, Owned).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The actual function that is called when using super is not known in the context of the class where it is used, although its type is known.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This is similar for ordinary virtual method lookup.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Base functions can be overridden by inheriting contracts to change their behavior if they are marked as `virtual`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The overriding function must then use the `override` keyword in the function header.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The overriding function may only change the visibility of the overridden function from `external` to `public`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The mutability may be changed to a more strict one following the order: `nonpayable` can be overridden by `view` and `pure`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] `payable` is an exception and cannot be changed to any other mutability.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] For multiple inheritance, the most derived base contracts that define the same function must be specified explicitly after the `override` keyword.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In other words, you have to specify all base contracts that define the same function and have not yet been overridden by another base contract (on some path through the inheritance graph).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] An explicit override specifier is not required if the function is defined in a common base contract or if there is a unique function in a common base contract that already overrides all other functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In this sense, an override path for a signature is a path through the inheritance graph that starts at the contract under consideration and ends at a contract mentioning a function with that signature that does not override.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If you do not mark a function that overrides as `virtual`, derived contracts can no longer change the behavior of that function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions with the `private` visibility cannot be `virtual`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Functions without implementation have to be marked `virtual` outside of interfaces.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In interfaces, all functions are automatically considered `virtual`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Starting from Solidity 0.8.8, the `override` keyword is not required when overriding an interface function, except for the case where the function is defined in multiple bases.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] While public state variables can override external functions, they themselves cannot be overridden.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Function modifiers can override each other.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This works in the same way as function overriding (except that there is no overloading for modifiers).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] `virtual` modifiers are deprecated and scheduled for removal.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] A constructor is an optional function declared with the `constructor` keyword which is executed upon contract creation, and where you can run contract initialization code.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Before the constructor code is executed, state variables are initialised to their specified value if you initialise them inline, or their default value if you do not.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] After the constructor has run, the final code of the contract is deployed to the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The deployment of the code costs additional gas linear to the length of the code.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This code includes all functions that are part of the public interface and all functions that are reachable from there through function calls.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] It does not include the constructor code or internal functions that are only called from the constructor.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If there is no constructor, the contract will assume the default constructor, which is equivalent to `constructor() {}`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] You can use internal parameters in a constructor (for example storage pointers).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In this case, the contract has to be marked abstract, because these parameters cannot be assigned valid values from outside but only through the constructors of derived contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Prior to version 0.4.22, constructors were defined as functions with the same name as the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This syntax was deprecated and is not allowed anymore in version 0.5.0.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Prior to version 0.7.0, you had to specify the visibility of constructors as either `internal` or `public`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The constructors of all the base contracts will be called following the linearization rules explained below.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If the base constructors have arguments, derived contracts need to specify all of them.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] One way is directly in the inheritance list (`is Base(7)`).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The other is in the way a modifier is invoked as part of the derived constructor (`Base(y * y)`).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The first way to do it is more convenient if the constructor argument is a constant and defines the behavior of the contract or describes it.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The second way has to be used if the constructor arguments of the base depend on those of the derived contract.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Arguments have to be given either in the inheritance list or in modifier-style in the derived constructor.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Specifying arguments in both places is an error.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If a derived contract does not specify the arguments to all of its base contracts’ constructors, it must be declared abstract.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In that case, when another contract derives from it, that other contract’s inheritance list or constructor must provide the necessary parameters for all base classes that haven’t had their parameters specified (otherwise, that other contract must be declared abstract as well).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] For example, in the above code snippet, see `Derived3` and `DerivedFromDerived`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Languages that allow multiple inheritance have to deal with several problems.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Solidity is similar to Python in that it uses C3 Linearization to force a specific order in the directed acyclic graph (DAG) of base classes.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] This results in the desirable property of monotonicity but disallows some inheritance graphs.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Especially, the order in which the base classes are given in the `is` directive is important: You have to list the direct base contracts in the order from “most base-like” to “most derived”.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Note that this order is the reverse of the one used in Python.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Another simplifying way to explain this is that when a function is called that is defined multiple times in different contracts, the given bases are searched from right to left (left to right in Python) in a depth-first manner, stopping at the first match.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] If a base contract has already been searched, it is skipped.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] In the following code, Solidity will give the error “Linearization of inheritance graph impossible”.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The reason for this is that `C` requests `X` to override `A` (by specifying `A, X` in this order), but `A` itself requests to override `X`, which is a contradiction that cannot be resolved.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] Due to the fact that you have to explicitly override a function that is inherited from multiple bases without a unique override, C3 linearization is not too important in practice.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] One area where inheritance linearization is especially important and perhaps not as clear is when there are multiple constructors in the inheritance hierarchy.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p02] The constructors will always be executed in the linearized order, regardless of the order in which their arguments are provided in the inheriting contract’s constructor.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Contracts must be marked as abstract when at least one of their functions is not implemented or when they do not provide arguments for all of their base contract constructors.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Even if this is not the case, a contract may still be marked abstract, such as when you do not intend for the contract to be created directly.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Abstract contracts are similar to Interfaces but an interface is more limited in what it can declare.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] An abstract contract is declared using the `abstract` keyword as shown in the following example.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Note that this contract needs to be defined as abstract, because the function `utterance()` is declared, but no implementation was provided (no implementation body `{ }` was given).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Such abstract contracts can not be instantiated directly.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] This is also true, if an abstract contract itself does implement all defined functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] If a contract inherits from an abstract contract and does not implement all non-implemented functions by overriding, it needs to be marked as abstract as well.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Note that a function without implementation is different from a Function Type even though their syntax looks very similar.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Abstract contracts decouple the definition of a contract from its implementation providing better extensibility and self-documentation and facilitating patterns like the Template method and removing code duplication.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Abstract contracts are useful in the same way that defining methods in an interface is useful.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] It is a way for the designer of the abstract contract to say “any child of mine must implement this method”.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Abstract contracts cannot override an implemented virtual function with an unimplemented one.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Interfaces are similar to abstract contracts, but they cannot have any functions implemented.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Some of these restrictions might be lifted in the future.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Interfaces are basically limited to what the Contract ABI can represent, and the conversion between the ABI and an interface should be possible without any information loss.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Contracts can inherit interfaces as they would inherit other contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] All functions declared in interfaces are implicitly `virtual` and any functions that override them do not need the `override` keyword.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] This does not automatically mean that an overriding function can be overridden again - this is only possible if the overriding function is marked `virtual`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Interfaces can inherit from other interfaces.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] This has the same rules as normal inheritance.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Types defined inside interfaces and other contract-like structures can be accessed from other contracts: `Token.TokenType` or `Token.Coin`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Interfaces have supported `enum` types since Solidity version 0.5.0, make sure the pragma version specifies this version as a minimum.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Libraries are similar to contracts, but their purpose is that they are deployed only once at a specific address and their code is reused using the `DELEGATECALL` (`CALLCODE` until Homestead) feature of the EVM.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] This means that if library functions are called, their code is executed in the context of the calling contract, i.e.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] `this` points to the calling contract, and especially the storage from the calling contract can be accessed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] As a library is an isolated piece of source code, it can only access state variables of the calling contract if they are explicitly supplied (it would have no way to name them, otherwise).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Library functions can only be called directly (i.e. without the use of `DELEGATECALL`) if they do not modify the state (i.e. if they are `view` or `pure` functions), because libraries are assumed to be stateless.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] In particular, it is not possible to destroy a library.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Until version 0.4.20, it was possible to destroy libraries by circumventing Solidity’s type system.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Starting from that version, libraries contain a mechanism that disallows state-modifying functions to be called directly (i.e. without `DELEGATECALL`).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Libraries can be seen as implicit base contracts of the contracts that use them.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] They will not be explicitly visible in the inheritance hierarchy, but calls to library functions look just like calls to functions of explicit base contracts (using qualified access like `L.f()`).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Of course, calls to internal functions use the internal calling convention, which means that all internal types can be passed and types stored in memory will be passed by reference and not copied.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] To realize this in the EVM, the code of internal library functions that are called from a contract and all functions called from therein will at compile time be included in the calling contract, and a regular `JUMP` call will be used instead of a `DELEGATECALL`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The inheritance analogy breaks down when it comes to public functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Calling a public library function with `L.f()` results in an external call (`DELEGATECALL` to be precise).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] In contrast, `A.f()` is an internal call when `A` is a base contract of the current contract.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The following example illustrates how to use libraries (but using a manual method, be sure to check out using for for a more advanced example to implement a set).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Of course, you do not have to follow this way to use libraries: they can also be used without defining struct data types.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Functions also work without any storage reference parameters, and they can have multiple storage reference parameters and in any position.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The calls to `Set.contains`, `Set.insert` and `Set.remove` are all compiled as calls (`DELEGATECALL`) to an external contract/library.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] If you use libraries, be aware that an actual external function call is performed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] `msg.sender`, `msg.value` and `this` will retain their values in this call, though (prior to Homestead, because of the use of `CALLCODE`, `msg.sender` and `msg.value` changed, though).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] It is possible to obtain the address of a library by converting the library type to the `address` type, i.e. using `address(LibraryName)`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] As the compiler does not know the address where the library will be deployed, the compiled hex code will contain placeholders of the form `__$30bbc0abd4d6364515865950d3e0d10953$__` (format was different <v0.5.0).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The placeholder is a 34 character prefix of the hex encoding of the keccak256 hash of the fully qualified library name, which would be for example `libraries/bigint.sol:BigInt` if the library was stored in a file called `bigint.sol` in a `libraries/` directory.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Such bytecode is incomplete and should not be deployed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Placeholders need to be replaced with actual addresses.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] You can do that by either passing them to the compiler when the library is being compiled or by using the linker to update an already compiled binary.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] See Library Linking for information on how to use the commandline compiler for linking.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] While external calls to public or external library functions are possible, the calling convention for such calls is considered to be internal to Solidity and not the same as specified for the regular contract ABI.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] External library functions support more argument types than external contract functions, for example recursive structs and storage pointers.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] For that reason, the function signatures used to compute the 4-byte selector are computed following an internal naming schema and arguments of types not supported in the contract ABI use an internal encoding.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The argument encoding is the same as for the regular contract ABI, except for storage pointers, which are encoded as a `uint256` value referring to the storage slot to which they point.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Similarly to the contract ABI, the selector consists of the first four bytes of the Keccak256-hash of the signature.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] As mentioned in the introduction, if a library’s code is executed using a `CALL` instead of a `DELEGATECALL` or `CALLCODE`, it will revert unless a `view` or `pure` function is called.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The EVM does not provide a direct way for a contract to detect whether it was called using `CALL` or not, but a contract can use the `ADDRESS` opcode to find out “where” it is currently running.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The generated code compares this address to the address used at construction time to determine the mode of calling.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] More specifically, the runtime code of a library always starts with a push instruction, which is a zero of 20 bytes at compilation time.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] When the deploy code runs, this constant is replaced in memory by the current address and this modified code is stored in the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] At runtime, this causes the deploy time address to be the first constant to be pushed onto the stack and the dispatcher code compares the current address against this constant for any non-view and non-pure function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] This means that the actual code stored on chain for a library is different from the code reported by the compiler as `deployedBytecode`.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The directive `using A for B` can be used to attach functions (`A`) as operators to user-defined value types or as member functions to any type (`B`).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The member functions receive the object they are called on as their first parameter (like the `self` variable in Python).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The operator functions receive operands as parameters.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] It is valid either at file level or inside a contract, at contract level.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] At file level, the second part, `B`, has to be an explicit type (without data location specifier).
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Inside contracts, you can also use `*` in place of the type (e.g.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] `using L for *;`), which has the effect that all functions of the library `L` are attached to *all* types.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] If you specify a library, *all* non-private functions in the library get attached, even those where the type of the first parameter does not match the type of the object.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The type is checked at the point the function is called and function overload resolution is performed.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] `using {f, g, h, L.t} for uint`), then the type (`uint`) has to be implicitly convertible to the first parameter of each of these functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] This check is performed even if none of these functions are called.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Note that private library functions can only be specified when `using for` is inside a library.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] `using {f as +} for T`), then the type (`T`) must be a user-defined value type and the definition must be a `pure` function.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Note that unary and binary `-` need separate definitions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The compiler will choose the right definition based on how the operator is invoked.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The `using A for B;` directive is active only within the current scope (either the contract or the current module/source unit), including within all of its functions, and has no effect outside of the contract or module in which it is used.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] When the directive is used at file level and applied to a user-defined type which was defined at file level in the same file, the word `global` can be added at the end.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] This will have the effect that the functions and operators are attached to the type everywhere the type is available (including other files), not only in the scope of the using statement.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Let us rewrite the set example from the Libraries section in this way, using file-level functions instead of library functions.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] It is also possible to extend built-in types in that way.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] Note that all external library calls are actual EVM function calls.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] This means that if you pass memory or value types, a copy will be performed, even in case of the `self` variable.
[src:solidity-lang/contracts-p03] The only situation where no copy will be performed is when storage reference variables are used or when internal library functions are called.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Let us begin with a basic example that sets the value of a variable and exposes it for other contracts to access.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It is fine if you do not understand everything right now, we will go into more details later.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The first line tells you that the source code is licensed under the GPL version 3.0.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Machine-readable license specifiers are important in a setting where publishing the source code is the default.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The next line specifies that the source code is written for Solidity version 0.4.16, or a newer version of the language up to, but not including version 0.9.0.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This is to ensure that the contract is not compilable with a new (breaking) compiler version, where it could behave differently.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Pragmas are common instructions for compilers about how to treat the source code (e.g. pragma once).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] A contract in the sense of Solidity is a collection of code (its *functions*) and data (its *state*) that resides at a specific address on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The line `uint storedData;` declares a state variable called `storedData` of type `uint` (*u*nsigned *int*eger of *256* bits).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] You can think of it as a single slot in a database that you can query and alter by calling functions of the code that manages the database.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In this example, the contract defines the functions `set` and `get` that can be used to modify or retrieve the value of the variable.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] To access a member (like a state variable) of the current contract, you do not typically add the `this.` prefix, you just access it directly via its name.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Unlike in some other languages, omitting it is not just a matter of style, it results in a completely different way to access the member, but more on this later.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This contract does not do much yet apart from (due to the infrastructure built by Ethereum) allowing anyone to store a single number that is accessible by anyone in the world without a (feasible) way to prevent you from publishing this number.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Anyone could call `set` again with a different value and overwrite your number, but the number is still stored in the history of the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Later, you will see how you can impose access restrictions so that only you can alter the number.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Be careful with using Unicode text, as similar looking (or even identical) characters can have different code points and as such are encoded as a different byte array.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] All identifiers (contract names, function names and variable names) are restricted to the ASCII character set.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It is possible to store UTF-8 encoded data in string variables.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The following contract implements the simplest form of a cryptocurrency.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The contract allows only its creator to create new coins (different issuance schemes are possible).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Anyone can send coins to each other without a need for registering with a username and password, all you need is an Ethereum keypair.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This contract introduces some new concepts, let us go through them one by one.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The line `address public minter;` declares a state variable of type address.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The `address` type is a 160-bit value that does not allow any arithmetic operations.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It is suitable for storing addresses of contracts, or a hash of the public half of a keypair belonging to externally-owned accounts.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The keyword `public` automatically generates a function that allows you to access the current value of the state variable from outside of the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Without this keyword, other contracts have no way to access the variable.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] You could add a function like the above yourself, but you would have a function and state variable with the same name.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] You do not need to do this, the compiler figures it out for you.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The next line, `mapping(address => uint) public balances;` also creates a public state variable, but it is a more complex datatype.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The mapping type maps addresses to unsigned integers.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Mappings can be seen as hash tables which are virtually initialized such that every possible key exists from the start and is mapped to a value whose byte-representation is all zeros.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] However, it is neither possible to obtain a list of all keys of a mapping, nor a list of all values.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Record what you added to the mapping, or use it in a context where this is not needed.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Or even better, keep a list, or use a more suitable data type.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The getter function created by the `public` keyword is more complex in the case of a mapping.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] You can use this function to query the balance of a single account.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The line `event Sent(address from, address to, uint amount);` declares an “event”, which is emitted in the last line of the function `send`.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Ethereum clients such as web applications can listen for these events emitted on the blockchain without much cost.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] As soon as it is emitted, the listener receives the arguments `from`, `to` and `amount`, which makes it possible to track transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The constructor is a special function that is executed during the creation of the contract and cannot be called afterwards.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In this case, it permanently stores the address of the person creating the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The `msg` variable (together with `tx` and `block`) is a special global variable that contains properties which allow access to the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] `msg.sender` is always the address where the current (external) function call came from.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The functions that make up the contract, and that users and contracts can call are `mint` and `send`.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The `mint` function sends an amount of newly created coins to another address.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The require function call defines conditions that reverts all changes if not met.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In this example, `require(msg.sender == minter);` ensures that only the creator of the contract can call `mint`.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In general, the creator can mint as many tokens as they like, but at some point, this will lead to a phenomenon called “overflow”.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Note that because of the default Checked arithmetic, the transaction would revert if the expression `balances[receiver] += amount;` overflows, i.e., when `balances[receiver] + amount` in arbitrary precision arithmetic is larger than the maximum value of `uint` (`2**256 - 1`).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This is also true for the statement `balances[receiver] += amount;` in the function `send`.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Errors allow you to provide more information to the caller about why a condition or operation failed.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Errors are used together with the revert statement.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The `revert` statement unconditionally aborts and reverts all changes, much like the require function.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Both approaches allow you to provide the name of an error and additional data which will be supplied to the caller (and eventually to the front-end application or block explorer) so that a failure can more easily be debugged or reacted upon.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The `send` function can be used by anyone (who already has some of these coins) to send coins to anyone else.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If the sender does *not* have enough coins to send, the condition in `require` evaluates to false, triggering a `revert` with the `InsufficientBalance` error.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This error supplies the requested amount and available balance to the caller, which front-end applications or block explorers can surface for debugging.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If you use this contract to send coins to an address, you will not see anything when you look at that address on a blockchain explorer, because the record that you sent coins and the changed balances are only stored in the data storage of this particular coin contract.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] By using events, you can create a “blockchain explorer” that tracks transactions and balances of your new coin, but you have to inspect the coin contract address and not the addresses of the coin owners.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Blockchains as a concept are not too hard to understand for programmers.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The reason is that most of the complications (mining, hashing, elliptic-curve cryptography, peer-to-peer networks, etc.) are just there to provide a certain set of features and promises for the platform.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Once you accept these features as given, you do not have to worry about the underlying technology - or do you have to know how Amazon’s AWS works internally in order to use it?
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] A blockchain is a globally shared, transactional database.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This means that everyone can read entries in the database just by participating in the network.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If you want to change something in the database, you have to create a so-called transaction which has to be accepted by all others.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The word transaction implies that the change you want to make (assume you want to change two values at the same time) is either not done at all or completely applied.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Furthermore, while your transaction is being applied to the database, no other transaction can alter it.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] As an example, imagine a table that lists the balances of all accounts in an electronic currency.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If a transfer from one account to another is requested, the transactional nature of the database ensures that if the amount is subtracted from one account, it is always added to the other account.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If due to whatever reason, adding the amount to the target account is not possible, the source account is also not modified.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Furthermore, a transaction is always cryptographically signed by the sender (creator).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This makes it straightforward to guard access to specific modifications of the database.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In the example of the electronic currency, a simple check ensures that only the person holding the keys to the account can transfer some compensation, e.g.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] One major obstacle to overcome is what (in Bitcoin terms) is called a “double-spend attack”: What happens if two transactions exist in the network that both want to empty an account?
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Only one of the transactions can be valid, typically the one that is accepted first.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The problem is that “first” is not an objective term in a peer-to-peer network.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The abstract answer to this is that you do not have to care.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] A globally accepted order of the transactions will be selected for you, solving the conflict.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The transactions will be bundled into what is called a “block” and then they will be executed and distributed among all participating nodes.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If two transactions contradict each other, the one that ends up being second will be rejected and not become part of the block.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] These blocks form a linear sequence in time, and that is where the word “blockchain” derives from.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Blocks are added to the chain at regular intervals, although these intervals may be subject to change in the future.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] For the most up-to-date information, it is recommended to monitor the network, for example, on Etherscan.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] As part of the “order selection mechanism”, which is called attestation, it may happen that blocks are reverted from time to time, but only at the “tip” of the chain.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The more blocks are added on top of a particular block, the less likely this block will be reverted.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] So it might be that your transactions are reverted and even removed from the blockchain, but the longer you wait, the less likely it will be.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Transactions are not guaranteed to be included in the next block or any specific future block, since it is not up to the submitter of a transaction, but up to the miners to determine in which block the transaction is included.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If you want to schedule future calls of your contract, you can use a smart contract automation tool or an oracle service.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The Ethereum Virtual Machine or EVM is the runtime environment for smart contracts in Ethereum.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It is not only sandboxed but actually completely isolated, which means that code running inside the EVM has no access to network, filesystem or other processes.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Smart contracts even have limited access to other smart contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] There are two kinds of accounts in Ethereum which share the same address space: **Externally-owned accounts** that are controlled by public-private key pairs (i.e. humans) and **contract accounts** which are controlled by the code stored together with the account.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The address of an externally-owned account is determined from the public key while the address of a contract is determined at the time the contract is created (it is derived from the creator address and the number of transactions sent from that address, the so-called “nonce”).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Regardless of whether or not the account stores code, the two types are treated equally by the EVM.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Every account has a persistent key-value store mapping 256-bit words to 256-bit words called **storage**.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Furthermore, every account has a **balance** in Ether (in “Wei” to be exact, `1 ether` is `10**18 wei`) which can be modified by sending transactions that include Ether.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] A transaction is a message that is sent from one account to another account (which might be the same or empty, see below).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It can include binary data (which is called “payload”) and Ether.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If the target account contains code, that code is executed and the payload is provided as input data.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If the target account is not set (the transaction does not have a recipient or the recipient is set to `null`), the transaction creates a **new contract**.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] As already mentioned, the address of that contract is not the zero address but an address derived from the sender and its number of transactions sent (the “nonce”).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The payload of such a contract creation transaction is taken to be EVM bytecode and executed.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The output data of this execution is permanently stored as the code of the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This means that in order to create a contract, you do not send the actual code of the contract, but in fact code that returns that code when executed.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] While a contract is being created, its code is still empty.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Because of that, you should not call back into the contract under construction until its constructor has finished executing.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Upon creation, each transaction is charged with a certain amount of **gas** that has to be paid for by the originator of the transaction (`tx.origin`).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] While the EVM executes the transaction, the gas is gradually depleted according to specific rules.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If the gas is used up at any point (i.e. it would be negative), an out-of-gas exception is triggered, which ends execution and reverts all modifications made to the state in the current call frame.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This mechanism incentivizes economical use of EVM execution time and also compensates EVM executors (i.e. miners / stakers) for their work.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Since each block has a maximum amount of gas, it also limits the amount of work needed to validate a block.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The **gas price** is a value set by the originator of the transaction, who has to pay `gas_price * gas` up front to the EVM executor.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If some gas is left after execution, it is refunded to the transaction originator.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In case of an exception that reverts changes, already used up gas is not refunded.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Since EVM executors can choose to include a transaction or not, transaction senders cannot abuse the system by setting a low gas price.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The Ethereum Virtual Machine has different areas where it can store data with the most prominent being storage, transient storage, memory and the stack.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Each account has a data area called **storage**, which is persistent between function calls and transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Storage is a key-value store that maps 256-bit words to 256-bit words.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It is not possible to enumerate storage from within a contract, it is comparatively costly to read, and even more to initialise and modify storage.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Because of this cost, you should minimize what you store in persistent storage to what the contract needs to run.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Store data like derived calculations, caching, and aggregates outside of the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] A contract can neither read nor write to any storage apart from its own.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Similar to storage, there is another data area called **transient storage**, where the main difference is that it is reset at the end of each transaction.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The values stored in this data location persist only across function calls originating from the first call of the transaction.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] When the transaction ends, the transient storage is reset and the values stored there become unavailable to calls in subsequent transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Despite this, the cost of reading and writing to transient storage is significantly lower than for storage.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The third data area is called **memory**, of which a contract obtains a freshly cleared instance for each message call.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Memory is linear and can be addressed at byte level, but reads are limited to a width of 256 bits, while writes can be either 8 bits or 256 bits wide.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Memory is expanded by a word (256-bit), when accessing (either reading or writing) a previously untouched memory word (i.e. any offset within a word).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] At the time of expansion, the cost in gas must be paid.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Memory is more costly the larger it grows (it scales quadratically).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The EVM is not a register machine but a stack machine, so all computations are performed on a data area called the **stack**.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It has a maximum size of 1024 elements and contains words of 256 bits.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Access to the stack is limited to the top end in the following way: It is possible to copy one of the topmost 16 elements to the top of the stack or swap the topmost element with one of the 16 elements below it.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] All other operations take the topmost two (or one, or more, depending on the operation) elements from the stack and push the result onto the stack.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Of course it is possible to move stack elements to storage or memory in order to get deeper access to the stack, but it is not possible to just access arbitrary elements deeper in the stack without first removing the top of the stack.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] There are also other data areas which are not as apparent as those discussed previously.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] However, they are routinely used during the execution of smart contract transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The calldata region is the data sent to a transaction as part of a smart contract transaction.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] For example, when creating a contract, calldata would be the constructor code of the new contract.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The parameters of external functions are always initially stored in calldata in an ABI-encoded form and only then decoded into the location specified in their declaration.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If declared as `memory`, the compiler will eagerly decode them into memory at the beginning of the function, while marking them as `calldata` means that this will be done lazily, only when accessed.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Value types and `storage` pointers are decoded directly onto the stack.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The returndata is the way a smart contract can return a value after a call.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In general, external Solidity functions use the `return` keyword to ABI-encode values into the returndata area.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The code is the region where the EVM instructions of a smart contract are stored.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Code is the bytes read, interpreted, and executed by the EVM during smart contract execution.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Instruction data stored in the code is persistent as part of a contract account state field.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Immutable and constant variables are stored in the code region.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] All references to immutables are replaced with the values assigned to them.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] A similar process is performed for constants which have their expressions inlined in the places where they are referenced in the smart contract code.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The instruction set of the EVM is kept minimal in order to avoid incorrect or inconsistent implementations which could cause consensus problems.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] All instructions operate on the basic data type, 256-bit words or on slices of memory (or other byte arrays).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The usual arithmetic, bit, logical and comparison operations are present.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Conditional and unconditional jumps are possible.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Furthermore, contracts can access relevant properties of the current block like its number and timestamp.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] For a complete list, please see the list of opcodes as part of the inline assembly documentation.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Contracts can call other contracts or send Ether to non-contract accounts by the means of message calls.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Message calls are similar to transactions, in that they have a source, a target, data payload, Ether, gas and return data.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In fact, every transaction consists of a top-level message call which in turn can create further message calls.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] A contract can decide how much of its remaining **gas** should be sent with the inner message call and how much it wants to retain.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If an out-of-gas exception happens in the inner call (or any other exception), this will be signaled by an error value put onto the stack.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In this case, only the gas sent together with the call is used up.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] In Solidity, the calling contract causes a manual exception by default in such situations, so that exceptions “bubble up” the call stack.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] As already said, the called contract (which can be the same as the caller) will receive a freshly cleared instance of memory and has access to the call payload - which will be provided in a separate area called the **calldata**.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] After it has finished execution, it can return data which will be stored at a location in the caller’s memory preallocated by the caller.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Calls are **limited** to a depth of 1024, which means that for more complex operations, loops should be preferred over recursive calls.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Furthermore, only 63/64th of the gas can be forwarded in a message call, which causes a depth limit of a little less than 1000 in practice.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] There exists a special variant of a message call, named **delegatecall** which is identical to a message call apart from the fact that the code at the target address is executed in the context (i.e. at the address) of the calling contract and `msg.sender` and `msg.value` do not change their values.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This means that a contract can dynamically load code from a different address at runtime.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Storage, current address and balance still refer to the calling contract, only the code is taken from the called address.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This makes it possible to implement the “library” feature in Solidity: Reusable library code that can be applied to a contract’s storage, e.g. in order to implement a complex data structure.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It is possible to store data in a specially indexed data structure that maps all the way up to the block level.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This feature called **logs** is used by Solidity in order to implement events.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Contracts cannot access log data after it has been created, but they can be efficiently accessed from outside the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Since some part of the log data is stored in bloom filters, it is possible to search for this data in an efficient and cryptographically secure way, so network peers that do not download the whole blockchain (so-called “light clients”) can still find these logs.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Contracts can even create other contracts using a special opcode (i.e. they do not simply call the zero address as a transaction would).
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The only difference between these **create calls** and normal message calls is that the payload data is executed and the result stored as code and the caller / creator receives the address of the new contract on the stack.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The only way to remove code from the blockchain is when a contract at that address performs the `selfdestruct` operation.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The remaining Ether stored at that address is sent to a designated target and then the storage and code is removed from the state.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Removing the contract in theory sounds like a good idea, but it is potentially dangerous, as if someone sends Ether to removed contracts, the Ether is forever lost.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] From `EVM >= Cancun` onwards, `selfdestruct` will **only** send all Ether in the account to the given recipient and not destroy the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The new behaviour is the result of a network-wide change that affects all contracts present on the Ethereum mainnet and testnets.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It is important to note that this change is dependent on the EVM version of the chain on which the contract is deployed.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The `--evm-version` setting used when compiling the contract has no bearing on it.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Also, note that the `selfdestruct` opcode has been deprecated in Solidity version 0.8.18, as recommended by EIP-6049.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] The deprecation is still in effect and the compiler will still emit warnings on its use.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Any use in newly deployed contracts is strongly discouraged even if the new behavior is taken into account.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Future changes to the EVM might further reduce the functionality of the opcode.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Even if a contract is removed by `selfdestruct`, it is still part of the history of the blockchain and probably retained by most Ethereum nodes.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] So using `selfdestruct` is not the same as deleting data from a hard disk.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Even if a contract’s code does not contain a call to `selfdestruct`, it can still perform that operation using `delegatecall` or `callcode`.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] If you want to deactivate your contracts, you should instead **disable** them by changing some internal state which causes all functions to revert.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] This makes it impossible to use the contract, as it returns Ether immediately.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] Different EVM-compatible chains might use a different set of precompiled contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/introduction-to-smart-contracts] It might also be possible that new precompiled contracts are added to the Ethereum main chain in the future, but you can reasonably expect them to always be in the range between `1` and `0xffff` (inclusive).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Solidity is a statically typed language, which means that the type of each variable (state and local) needs to be specified.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Solidity provides several elementary types which can be combined to form complex types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] In addition, types can interact with each other in expressions containing operators.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For a quick reference of the various operators, see Order of Precedence of Operators.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The concept of “undefined” or “null” values does not exist in Solidity, but newly declared variables always have a default value dependent on its type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] To handle any unexpected values, you should use the revert function to revert the whole transaction, or return a tuple with a second `bool` value denoting success.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The following are called value types because their variables will always be passed by value, i.e. they are always copied when they are used as function arguments or in assignments.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Unlike reference types, value type declarations do not specify a data location since they are small enough to be stored on the stack.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Those are by default located in storage, but can also be marked as transient, constant or immutable.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `bool`: The possible values are constants `true` and `false`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The operators `||` and `&&` apply the common short-circuiting rules.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This means that in the expression `f(x) || g(y)`, if `f(x)` evaluates to `true`, `g(y)` will not be evaluated even if it may have side-effects.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `int` / `uint`: Signed and unsigned integers of various sizes.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Keywords `uint8` to `uint256` in steps of `8` (unsigned of 8 up to 256 bits) and `int8` to `int256`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `uint` and `int` are aliases for `uint256` and `int256`, respectively.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For an integer type `X`, you can use `type(X).min` and `type(X).max` to access the minimum and maximum value representable by the type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Integers in Solidity are restricted to a certain range.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] There are two modes in which arithmetic is performed on these types: The “wrapping” or “unchecked” mode and the “checked” mode.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] By default, arithmetic is always “checked”, meaning that if an operation’s result falls outside the value range of the type, the call is reverted through a failing assertion.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] You can switch to “unchecked” mode using `unchecked { ... }`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] More details can be found in the section about unchecked.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The value of a comparison is the one obtained by comparing the integer value.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Bit operations are performed on the two’s complement representation of the number.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The result of a shift operation has the type of the left operand, truncating the result to match the type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The right operand must be of unsigned type, trying to shift by a signed type will produce a compilation error.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Shifts can be “simulated” using multiplication by powers of two in the following way.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Note that the truncation to the type of the left operand is always performed at the end, but not mentioned explicitly.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Before version `0.5.0` a right shift `x >> y` for negative `x` was equivalent to the mathematical expression `x / 2**y` rounded towards zero, i.e., right shifts used rounding up (towards zero) instead of rounding down (towards negative infinity).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Overflow checks are never performed for shift operations as they are done for arithmetic operations.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Instead, the result is always truncated.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] By default, all arithmetic is checked for under- or overflow, but this can be disabled using the unchecked block, resulting in wrapping arithmetic.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] More details can be found in that section.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The expression `-x` is equivalent to `(T(0) - x)` where `T` is the type of `x`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The value of `-x` can be positive if `x` is negative.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If you have `int x = type(int).min;`, then `-x` does not fit the positive range.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This means that `unchecked { assert(-x == x); }` works, and the expression `-x` when used in checked mode will result in a failing assertion.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Since the type of the result of an operation is always the type of one of the operands, division on integers always results in an integer.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] In Solidity, division rounds towards zero.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Note that in contrast, division on literals results in fractional values of arbitrary precision.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This check can **not** be disabled through `unchecked { ... }`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The expression `type(int).min / (-1)` is the only case where division causes an overflow.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] In checked arithmetic mode, this will cause a failing assertion, while in wrapping mode, the value will be `type(int).min`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The modulo operation `a % n` yields the remainder `r` after the division of the operand `a` by the operand `n`, where `q = int(a / n)` and `r = a - (n * q)`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Exponentiation is only available for unsigned types in the exponent.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The resulting type of an exponentiation is always equal to the type of the base.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Please take care that it is large enough to hold the result and prepare for potential assertion failures or wrapping behavior.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] In checked mode, exponentiation only uses the comparatively cheap `exp` opcode for small bases.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For the cases of `x**3`, the expression `x*x*x` might be cheaper.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] In any case, gas cost tests and the use of the optimizer are advisable.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Note that `0**0` is defined by the EVM as `1`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Fixed point numbers are not fully supported by Solidity yet.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] They can be declared, but cannot be assigned to or from.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `fixed` / `ufixed`: Signed and unsigned fixed point number of various sizes.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Keywords `ufixedMxN` and `fixedMxN`, where `M` represents the number of bits taken by the type and `N` represents how many decimal points are available.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `M` must be divisible by 8 and goes from 8 to 256 bits.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `N` must be between 0 and 80, inclusive.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `ufixed` and `fixed` are aliases for `ufixed128x18` and `fixed128x18`, respectively.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Generally, in floating point almost the entire space is used to represent the number, while only a small number of bits define where the decimal point is.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The idea behind this distinction is that `address payable` is an address you can send Ether to, while you are not supposed to send Ether to a plain `address`, for example because it might be a smart contract that was not built to accept Ether.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Implicit conversions from `address payable` to `address` are allowed, whereas conversions from `address` to `address payable` must be explicit via `payable(<address>)`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Explicit conversions to and from `address` are allowed for `uint160`, integer literals, `bytes20` and contract types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Only expressions of type `address` and contract type can be converted to the type `address payable` via the explicit conversion `payable(...)`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For contract-type, this conversion is only allowed if the contract can receive Ether, i.e., the contract either has a receive or a payable fallback function.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Note that `payable(0)` is valid and is an exception to this rule.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If you need a variable of type `address` and plan to send Ether to it, then declare its type as `address payable` to make this requirement visible.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Also, try to make this distinction or conversion as early as possible.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The distinction between `address` and `address payable` was introduced in version 0.5.0.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Also starting from that version, contracts are not implicitly convertible to the `address` type, but can still be explicitly converted to `address` or to `address payable`, if they have a receive or payable fallback function.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If you convert a type that uses a larger byte size to an `address`, for example `bytes32`, then the `address` is truncated.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] To reduce conversion ambiguity, starting with version 0.4.24, the compiler will force you to make the truncation explicit in the conversion.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Mixed-case hexadecimal numbers conforming to EIP-55 are automatically treated as literals of the `address` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For a quick reference of all members of address, see Members of Address Types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] You can implicitly convert contracts to contracts they inherit from.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Contracts can be explicitly converted to and from the `address` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Explicit conversion to and from the `address payable` type is only possible if the contract type has a receive or payable fallback function.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The conversion is still performed using `address(x)`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If the contract type does not have a receive or payable fallback function, the conversion to `address payable` can be done using `payable(address(x))`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] You can find more information in the section about the address type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Before version 0.5.0, contracts directly derived from the address type and there was no distinction between `address` and `address payable`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If you declare a local variable of contract type (`MyContract c`), you can call functions on that contract.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Take care to assign it from somewhere that is the same contract type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] You can also instantiate contracts (which means they are newly created).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] You can find more details in the ‘Contracts via new’ section.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The data representation of a contract is identical to that of the `address` type and this type is also used in the ABI.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The members of contract types are the external functions of the contract including any state variables marked as `public`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For a contract `C` you can use `type(C)` to access type information about the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The value types `bytes1`, `bytes2`, `bytes3`, …, `bytes32` hold a sequence of bytes from one to up to 32.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The shifting operator works with unsigned integer type as right operand (but returns the type of the left operand), which denotes the number of bits to shift by.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Shifting by a signed type will produce a compilation error.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The type `bytes1[]` is an array of bytes, but due to padding rules, it wastes 31 bytes of space for each element (except in storage).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] It is better to use the `bytes` type instead.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Prior to version 0.8.0, `byte` used to be an alias for `bytes1`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Hexadecimal literals that pass the address checksum test, for example `0xdCad3a6d3569DF655070DEd06cb7A1b2Ccd1D3AF` are of `address` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Hexadecimal literals that are between 39 and 41 digits long and do not pass the checksum test produce an error.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] You can prepend (for integer types) or append (for bytesNN types) zeros to remove the error.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The mixed-case address checksum format is defined in EIP-55.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Integer literals are formed from a sequence of digits in the range 0-9.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Octal literals do not exist in Solidity and leading zeros are invalid.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Decimal fractional literals are formed by a `.` with at least one number after the decimal point.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Scientific notation in the form of `2e10` is also supported, where the mantissa can be fractional but the exponent has to be an integer.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The literal `MeE` is equivalent to `M * 10**E`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Underscores can be used to separate the digits of a numeric literal to aid readability.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For example, decimal `123_000`, hexadecimal `0x2eff_abde`, scientific decimal notation `1_2e345_678` are all valid.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Underscores are only allowed between two digits and only one consecutive underscore is allowed.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] There is no additional semantic meaning added to a number literal containing underscores, the underscores are ignored.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Number literal expressions retain arbitrary precision until they are converted to a non-literal type (i.e. by using them together with anything other than a number literal expression (like boolean literals) or by explicit conversion).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This means that computations do not overflow and divisions do not truncate in number literal expressions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For example, `(2**800 + 1) - 2**800` results in the constant `1` (of type `uint8`) although intermediate results would not even fit the machine word size.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Furthermore, `.5 * 8` results in the integer `4` (although non-integers were used in between).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] You might expect expressions like `255 + (true ?
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] 1 : 0)` or `255 + [1, 2, 3][0]` to be equivalent to using the literal 256 directly, but in fact they are computed within the type `uint8` and can overflow.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Any operator that can be applied to integers can also be applied to number literal expressions as long as the operands are integers.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If any of the two is fractional, bit operations are disallowed and exponentiation is disallowed if the exponent is fractional (because that might result in a non-rational number).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Shifts and exponentiation with literal numbers as left (or base) operand and integer types as the right (exponent) operand are always performed in the `uint256` (for non-negative literals) or `int256` (for a negative literals) type, regardless of the type of the right (exponent) operand.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Division on integer literals used to truncate in Solidity prior to version 0.4.0, but it now converts into a rational number, i.e.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Solidity has a number literal type for each rational number.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Integer literals and rational number literals belong to number literal types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Moreover, all number literal expressions (i.e. the expressions that contain only number literals and operators) belong to number literal types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] So the number literal expressions `1 + 2` and `2 + 1` both belong to the same number literal type for the rational number three.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Number literal expressions are converted into a non-literal type as soon as they are used with non-literal expressions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Disregarding types, the value of the expression assigned to `b` below evaluates to an integer.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Because `a` is of type `uint128`, the expression `2.5 + a` has to have a proper type, though.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Since there is no common type for the type of `2.5` and `uint128`, the Solidity compiler does not accept this code.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] String literals are written with either double or single-quotes (`"foo"` or `'bar'`), and they can also be split into multiple consecutive parts (`"foo" "bar"` is equivalent to `"foobar"`) which can be helpful when dealing with long strings.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] They do not imply trailing zeroes as in C; `"foo"` represents three bytes, not four.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] As with integer literals, their type can vary, but they are implicitly convertible to `bytes1`, …, `bytes32`, if they fit, to `bytes` and to `string`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For example, with `bytes32 samevar = "stringliteral"` the string literal is interpreted in its raw byte form when assigned to a `bytes32` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] String literals can only contain printable ASCII characters, which means the characters between and including 0x20 ..
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `\xNN` takes a hex value and inserts the appropriate byte, while `\uNNNN` takes a Unicode codepoint and inserts an UTF-8 sequence.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Until version 0.8.0 there were three additional escape sequences: `\b`, `\f` and `\v`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] They are commonly available in other languages but rarely needed in practice.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If you do need them, they can still be inserted via hexadecimal escapes, i.e.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] `\x08`, `\x0c` and `\x0b`, respectively, just as any other ASCII character.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The string in the following example has a length of ten bytes.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] It starts with a newline byte, followed by a double quote, a single quote a backslash character and then (without separator) the character sequence `abcdef`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Any Unicode line terminator which is not a newline (i.e.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] LF, VF, FF, CR, NEL, LS, PS) is considered to terminate the string literal.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Newline only terminates the string literal if it is not preceded by a `\`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] While regular string literals can only contain ASCII, Unicode literals – prefixed with the keyword `unicode` – can contain any valid UTF-8 sequence.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] They also support the very same escape sequences as regular string literals.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Hexadecimal literals are prefixed with the keyword `hex` and are enclosed in double or single-quotes (`hex"001122FF"`, `hex'0011_22_FF'`).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Their content must be hexadecimal digits which can optionally use a single underscore as separator between byte boundaries.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The value of the literal will be the binary representation of the hexadecimal sequence.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Hexadecimal literals in some ways behave like string literals but are not implicitly convertible to the `string` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Enums are one way to create a user-defined type in Solidity.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] They are explicitly convertible to and from all integer types but implicit conversion is not allowed.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The explicit conversion from integer checks at runtime that the value lies inside the range of the enum and causes a Panic error otherwise.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Enums require at least one member, and its default value when declared is the first member.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Enums cannot have more than 256 members.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The data representation is the same as for enums in C: The options are represented by subsequent unsigned integer values starting from `0`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Using `type(NameOfEnum).min` and `type(NameOfEnum).max` you can get the smallest and respectively largest value of the given enum.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Enums can also be declared on the file level, outside of contract or library definitions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] A user-defined value type allows creating a zero cost abstraction over an elementary value type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This is similar to an alias, but with stricter type requirements.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] A user-defined value type is defined using `type C is V`, where `C` is the name of the newly introduced type and `V` has to be a built-in value type (the “underlying type”).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The function `C.wrap` is used to convert from the underlying type to the custom type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Similarly, the function `C.unwrap` is used to convert from the custom type to the underlying type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The type `C` does not have any operators or attached member functions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] In particular, even the operator `==` is not defined.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Explicit and implicit conversions to and from other types are disallowed.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The data-representation of values of such types are inherited from the underlying type and the underlying type is also used in the ABI.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The following example illustrates a custom type `UFixed256x18` representing a decimal fixed point type with 18 decimals and a minimal library to do arithmetic operations on the type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Function types are the types of functions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Variables of a function type can be assigned from functions and function parameters of function type can be used to pass functions to and return functions from function calls.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Internal functions can only be called inside the current contract (more specifically, inside the current code unit, which also includes internal library functions and inherited functions) because they cannot be executed outside of the context of the current contract.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Calling an internal function is realized by jumping to its entry label, just like when calling a function of the current contract internally.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] External functions consist of an address and a function signature and they can be passed via and returned from external function calls.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Note that public functions of the current contract can be used both as an internal and as an external function.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] To use `f` as an internal function, just use `f`, if you want to use its external form, use `this.f`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If a function type variable is not initialised, calling it results in a Panic error.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The same happens if you call a function after using `delete` on it.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Lambda or inline functions are planned but not yet supported.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] In contrast to the parameter types, the return types cannot be empty - if the function type should not return anything, the whole `returns (<return types>)` part has to be omitted.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] By default, function types are internal, so the `internal` keyword can be omitted.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Note that this only applies to function types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Visibility has to be specified explicitly for functions defined in contracts, they do not have a default.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] A function type `A` is implicitly convertible to a function type `B` if and only if their parameter types are identical, their return types are identical, their internal/external property is identical and the state mutability of `A` is more restrictive than the state mutability of `B`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] No other conversions between function types are possible.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The rule about `payable` and `non-payable` might be a little confusing, but in essence, if a function is `payable`, this means that it also accepts a payment of zero Ether, so it also is `non-payable`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] On the other hand, a `non-payable` function will reject Ether sent to it, so `non-payable` functions cannot be converted to `payable` functions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] To clarify, rejecting ether is more restrictive than not rejecting ether.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This means you can override a payable function with a non-payable but not the other way around.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Additionally, When you define a `non-payable` function pointer, the compiler does not enforce that the pointed function will actually reject ether.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Instead, it enforces that the function pointer is never used to send ether.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Which makes it possible to assign a `payable` function pointer to a `non-payable` function pointer ensuring both types behave the same way, i.e, both cannot be used to send ether.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] If external function types are used outside of the context of Solidity, they are treated as the `function` type, which encodes the address followed by the function identifier together in a single `bytes24` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] A function of an internal type can be assigned to a variable of an internal function type regardless of where it is defined.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This includes private, internal and public functions of both contracts and libraries as well as free functions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] External function types, on the other hand, are only compatible with public and external contract functions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] External functions with `calldata` parameters are incompatible with external function types with `calldata` parameters.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] They are compatible with the corresponding types with `memory` parameters instead.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For example, there is no function that can be pointed at by a value of type `function (string calldata) external` while `function (string memory) external` can point at both `function f(string memory) external {}` and `function g(string calldata) external {}`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This is because for both locations the arguments are passed to the function in the same way.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The caller cannot pass its calldata directly to an external function and always ABI-encodes the arguments into memory.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Marking the parameters as `calldata` only affects the implementation of the external function and is meaningless in a function pointer on the caller’s side.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Comparison of internal function pointers can have unexpected results in the legacy pipeline with the optimizer enabled, as it can collapse identical functions into one, which will then lead to said function pointers comparing as equal instead of not.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Such comparisons are not advised, and will lead to the compiler issuing a warning, until the next breaking release (0.9.0), when the warning will be upgraded to an error, thereby making such comparisons disallowed.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Libraries are excluded because they require a `delegatecall` and use a different ABI convention for their selectors.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Functions declared in interfaces do not have definitions so pointing at them does not make sense either.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] External (or public) functions used to have the additional members `.gas(uint)` and `.value(uint)`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] These were deprecated in Solidity 0.6.2 and removed in Solidity 0.7.0.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Instead use `{gas: ...}` and `{value: ...}` to specify the amount of gas or the amount of wei sent to a function, respectively.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] See External Function Calls for more information.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] An important aspect to consider when using values of function types is whether the value will remain valid if the underlying code changes.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] External function types can be considered as stable as contract’s ABI, which makes them very portable.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Their ABI representation always consists of a contract address and a function selector and it is perfectly safe to store them long-term or pass them between contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] While it is possible for the referenced function to change or disappear, a direct external call would be affected the same way, so there is no additional risk in such use.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] In case of internal functions, however, the value is an identifier that is strongly tied to contract’s bytecode.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The actual representation of the identifier is an implementation detail and may change between compiler versions or even between different backends.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Values assigned under a given representation are deterministic (i.e. guaranteed to remain the same as long as the source code is the same) but are easily affected by changes such as adding, removing or reordering of functions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The compiler is also free to remove internal functions that are never used, which may affect other identifiers.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Some representations, e.g. one where identifiers are simply jump targets, may be affected by virtually any change, even one completely unrelated to internal functions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] To counter this, the language limits the use of internal function types outside of the context in which they are valid.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] This is why internal function types cannot be used as parameters of external functions (or in any other way that is exposed in contract’s ABI).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] However, there are still situations where it is up to the user to decide whether their use is safe or not.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] For example long-term storage of such values in state variables is discouraged, but may be safe if the contract code is never going to be updated.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] It is also always possible to side-step any safeguards by using inline assembly.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Such use always needs careful consideration.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] The removal of unused internal functions only takes into account explicit references to such functions by name.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p01] Implicit references, such as assigning a new value to a function type variable in inline assembly may still lead to the removal of the function if it is not also referenced explicitly elsewhere in the source.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Values of reference type can be modified through multiple different names.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Contrast this with value types where you get an independent copy whenever a variable of value type is used.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Because of that, reference types have to be handled more carefully than value types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Currently, reference types comprise structs, arrays and mappings.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] An assignment or type conversion that changes the data location will always incur an automatic copy operation, while assignments inside the same data location only copy in some cases for storage types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Every reference type has an additional annotation, the “data location”, about where it is stored.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] There are three data locations: `memory`, `storage` and `calldata`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Calldata is a non-modifiable, non-persistent area where function arguments are stored, and behaves mostly like memory.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `transient` is not yet supported as a data location for reference types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you can, try to use `calldata` as data location because it will avoid copies and also makes sure that the data cannot be modified.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Arrays and structs with `calldata` data location can also be returned from functions, but it is not possible to allocate such types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Arrays and structs with `calldata` location declared in a function body or as its return parameters must be assigned before being used or returned.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] There are certain cases in which non-trivial control flow is used and the compiler can’t properly detect the initialization.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] A common workaround in such cases is to assign the affected variable to itself before the correct initialization takes place.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Prior to version 0.6.9 data location for reference-type arguments was limited to `calldata` in external functions, `memory` in public functions and either `memory` or `storage` in internal and private ones.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Now `memory` and `calldata` are allowed in all functions regardless of their visibility.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Constructor parameters cannot use `calldata` as their data location.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Prior to version 0.5.0 the data location could be omitted, and would default to different locations depending on the kind of variable, function type, etc., but all complex types must now give an explicit data location.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Arrays can have a compile-time fixed size, or they can have a dynamic size.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The type of an array of fixed size `k` and element type `T` is written as `T[k]`, and an array of dynamic size as `T[]`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] For example, an array of 5 dynamic arrays of `uint` is written as `uint[][5]`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The notation is reversed compared to some other languages.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In Solidity, `X[3]` is always an array containing three elements of type `X`, even if `X` is itself an array.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This is not the case in other languages such as C.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Indices are zero-based, and access is in the opposite direction of the declaration.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] For example, if you have a variable `uint[][5] memory x`, you access the seventh `uint` in the third dynamic array using `x[2][6]`, and to access the third dynamic array, use `x[2]`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Again, if you have an array `T[5] a` for a type `T` that can also be an array, then `a[2]` always has type `T`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Array elements can be of any type, including mapping or struct.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The general restrictions for types apply, in that mappings can only be stored in the `storage` data location and publicly-visible functions need parameters that are ABI types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is possible to mark state variable arrays `public` and have Solidity create a getter.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The numeric index becomes a required parameter for the getter.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Accessing an array past its end causes a failing assertion.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Methods `.push()` and `.push(value)` can be used to append a new element at the end of a dynamically-sized array, where `.push()` appends a zero-initialized element and returns a reference to it.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Dynamically-sized arrays can only be resized in storage.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In memory, such arrays can be of arbitrary size but the size cannot be changed once an array is allocated.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Variables of type `bytes` and `string` are special arrays.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The `bytes` type is similar to `bytes1[]`, but it is packed tightly in calldata and memory.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `string` is equal to `bytes` but does not allow length or index access.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Solidity does not have string manipulation functions, but there are third-party string libraries.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] You can also compare two strings by their keccak256-hash using `keccak256(abi.encodePacked(s1)) == keccak256(abi.encodePacked(s2))` and concatenate two strings using `string.concat(s1, s2)`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] You should use `bytes` over `bytes1[]` because it is cheaper, since using `bytes1[]` in `memory` adds 31 padding bytes between the elements.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Note that in `storage`, the padding is absent due to tight packing, see bytes and string.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] As a general rule, use `bytes` for arbitrary-length raw byte data and `string` for arbitrary-length string (UTF-8) data.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you can limit the length to a certain number of bytes, always use one of the value types `bytes1` to `bytes32` because they are much cheaper.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you want to access the byte-representation of a string `s`, use `bytes(s).length` / `bytes(s)[7] = 'x';`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Keep in mind that you are accessing the low-level bytes of the UTF-8 representation, and not the individual characters.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] You can concatenate an arbitrary number of `string` values using `string.concat`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The function returns a single `string memory` array that contains the contents of the arguments without padding.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you want to use parameters of other types that are not implicitly convertible to `string`, you need to convert them to `string` first.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Analogously, the `bytes.concat` function can concatenate an arbitrary number of `bytes` or `bytes1 ... bytes32` values.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The function returns a single `bytes memory` array that contains the contents of the arguments without padding.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you want to use string parameters or other types that are not implicitly convertible to `bytes`, you need to convert them to `bytes` or `bytes1`/…/`bytes32` first.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you call `string.concat` or `bytes.concat` without arguments they return an empty array.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Memory arrays with dynamic length can be created using the `new` operator.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] As opposed to storage arrays, it is **not** possible to resize memory arrays (e.g. the `.push` member functions are not available).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] You either have to calculate the required size in advance or create a new memory array and copy every element.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] As all variables in Solidity, the elements of newly allocated arrays are always initialized with the default value.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] An array literal is a comma-separated list of one or more expressions, enclosed in square brackets (`[...]`).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is always a statically-sized memory array whose length is the number of expressions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The base type of the array is the type of the first expression on the list such that all other expressions can be implicitly converted to it.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is a type error if this is not possible.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is not enough that there is a type all the elements can be converted to.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] One of the elements has to be of that type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In the example below, the type of `[1, 2, 3]` is `uint8[3] memory`, because the type of each of these constants is `uint8`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you want the result to be a `uint[3] memory` type, you need to convert the first element to `uint`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The array literal `[1, -1]` is invalid because the type of the first expression is `uint8` while the type of the second is `int8` and they cannot be implicitly converted to each other.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] To make it work, you can use `[int8(1), -1]`, for example.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is planned to remove this restriction in the future, but it creates some complications because of how arrays are passed in the ABI.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Arrays have a `length` member that contains their number of elements.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The length of memory arrays is fixed (but dynamic, i.e. it can depend on runtime parameters) once they are created.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Dynamic storage arrays and `bytes` (not `string`) have a member function called `push()` that you can use to append a zero-initialised element at the end of the array.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It returns a reference to the element, so that it can be used like `x.push().t = 2` or `x.push() = b`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Dynamic storage arrays and `bytes` (not `string`) have a member function called `push(x)` that you can use to append a given element at the end of the array.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Dynamic storage arrays and `bytes` (not `string`) have a member function called `pop()` that you can use to remove an element from the end of the array.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This also implicitly calls delete on the removed element.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Increasing the length of a storage array by calling `push()` has constant gas costs because storage is zero-initialised, while decreasing the length by calling `pop()` has a cost that depends on the “size” of the element being removed.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If that element is an array, it can be very costly, because it includes explicitly clearing the removed elements similar to calling delete on them.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] To use arrays of arrays in external (instead of public) functions, you need to activate ABI coder v2.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In EVM versions before Byzantium, it was not possible to access dynamic arrays returned from function calls.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you call functions that return dynamic arrays, make sure to use an EVM that is set to Byzantium mode.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] When working with storage arrays, you need to take care to avoid dangling references.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] A dangling reference is a reference that points to something that no longer exists or has been moved without updating the reference.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The write in `ptr.push(0x42)` will **not** revert, despite the fact that `ptr` no longer refers to a valid element of `s`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Since the compiler assumes that unused storage is always zeroed, a subsequent `s.push()` will not explicitly write zeroes to storage, so the last element of `s` after that `push()` will have length `1` and contain `0x42` as its first element.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Note that Solidity does not allow to declare references to value types in storage.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] These kinds of explicit dangling references are restricted to nested reference types.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is always safer to only assign to storage once per statement and to avoid complex expressions on the left-hand-side of an assignment.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] You need to take particular care when dealing with references to elements of `bytes` arrays, since a `.push()` on a bytes array may switch from short to long layout in storage.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Here, when the first `x.push()` is evaluated, `x` is still stored in short layout, thereby `x.push()` returns a reference to an element in the first storage slot of `x`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] However, the second `x.push()` switches the bytes array to large layout.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Now the element that `x.push()` referred to is in the data area of the array while the reference still points at its original location, which is now a part of the length field and the assignment will effectively garble the length of `x`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] To be safe, only enlarge bytes arrays by at most one element during a single assignment and do not simultaneously index-access the array in the same statement.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] While the above describes the behavior of dangling storage references in the current version of the compiler, any code with dangling references should be considered to have *undefined behavior*.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In particular, this means that any future version of the compiler may change the behavior of code that involves dangling references.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Be sure to avoid dangling references in your code!
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Array slices are a view on a contiguous portion of an array.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] They are written as `x[start:end]`, where `start` and `end` are expressions resulting in a uint256 type (or implicitly convertible to it).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The first element of the slice is `x[start]` and the last element is `x[end - 1]`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If `start` is greater than `end` or if `end` is greater than the length of the array, an exception is thrown.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Both `start` and `end` are optional: `start` defaults to `0` and `end` defaults to the length of the array.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] They are implicitly convertible to arrays of their underlying type and support index access.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Index access is not absolute in the underlying array, but relative to the start of the slice.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Array slices do not have a type name which means no variable can have an array slices as type, they only exist in intermediate expressions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] As of now, array slices are only implemented for calldata arrays.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The contract does not provide the full functionality of a crowdfunding contract, but it contains the basic concepts necessary to understand structs.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Struct types can be used inside mappings and arrays and they can themselves contain mappings and arrays.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is not possible for a struct to contain a member of its own type, although the struct itself can be the value type of a mapping member or it can contain a dynamically-sized array of its type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This restriction is necessary, as the size of the struct has to be finite.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Note how in all the functions, a struct type is assigned to a local variable with data location `storage`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This does not copy the struct but only stores a reference so that assignments to members of the local variable actually write to the state.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Of course, you can also directly access the members of the struct without assigning it to a local variable, as in `campaigns[campaignID].amount = 0`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Until Solidity 0.7.0, memory-structs containing members of storage-only types (e.g. mappings) were allowed and assignments like `campaigns[campaignID] = Campaign(beneficiary, goal, 0, 0)` in the example above would work and just silently skip those members.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Mapping types use the syntax `mapping(KeyType KeyName? => ValueType ValueName?)` and variables of mapping type are declared using the syntax `mapping(KeyType KeyName? => ValueType ValueName?) VariableName`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The `KeyType` can be any built-in value type, `bytes`, `string`, or any contract or enum type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Other user-defined or complex types, such as mappings, structs or array types are not allowed.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `ValueType` can be any type, including mappings, arrays and structs.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `KeyName` and `ValueName` are optional (so `mapping(KeyType => ValueType)` works as well) and can be any valid identifier that is not a type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] You can think of mappings as hash tables, which are virtually initialised such that every possible key exists and is mapped to a value whose byte-representation is all zeros, a type’s default value.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The similarity ends there, the key data is not stored in a mapping, only its `keccak256` hash is used to look up the value.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Because of this, mappings do not have a length or a concept of a key or value being set, and therefore cannot be erased without extra information regarding the assigned keys (see Clearing Mappings).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Mappings can only have a data location of `storage` and thus are allowed for state variables, as storage reference types in functions, or as parameters for library functions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] They cannot be used as parameters or return parameters of contract functions that are publicly visible.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] These restrictions are also true for arrays and structs that contain mappings.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] You can mark state variables of mapping type as `public` and Solidity creates a getter for you.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The `KeyType` becomes a parameter with name `KeyName` (if specified) for the getter.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If `ValueType` is a value type or a struct, the getter returns `ValueType` with name `ValueName` (if specified).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If `ValueType` is an array or a mapping, the getter has one parameter for each `KeyType`, recursively.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In the example below, the `MappingExample` contract defines a public `balances` mapping, with the key type an `address`, and a value type a `uint`, mapping an Ethereum address to an unsigned integer value.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] As `uint` is a value type, the getter returns a value that matches the type, which you can see in the `MappingUser` contract that returns the value at the specified address.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The example below is a simplified version of an ERC20 token.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `_allowances` is an example of a mapping type inside another mapping type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In the example below, the optional `KeyName` and `ValueName` are provided for the mapping.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It does not affect any contract functionality or bytecode, it only sets the `name` field for the inputs and outputs in the ABI for the mapping’s getter.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The example below uses `_allowances` to record the amount someone else is allowed to withdraw from your account.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] You cannot iterate over mappings, i.e. you cannot enumerate their keys.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is possible, though, to implement a data structure on top of them and iterate over that.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] For example, the code below implements an `IterableMapping` library that the `User` contract then adds data to, and the `sum` function iterates over to sum all the values.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Arithmetic and bit operators can be applied even if the two operands do not have the same type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] For example, you can compute `y = x + z`, where `x` is a `uint8` and `z` has the type `uint32`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] 3. otherwise, the operation is not allowed.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In case one of the operands is a literal number it is first converted to its “mobile type”, which is the smallest type that can hold the value (unsigned types of the same bit-width are considered “smaller” than the signed types).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If both are literal numbers, the operation is computed with effectively unlimited precision in that the expression is evaluated to whatever precision is necessary so that none is lost when the result is used with a non-literal type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The operator’s result type is the same as the type the operation is performed in, except for comparison operators where the result is always `bool`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The operators `**` (exponentiation), `<<` and `>>` use the type of the left operand for the operation and the result.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The ternary operator is used in expressions of the form `<expression> ? <trueExpression> : <falseExpression>`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It evaluates one of the latter two given expressions depending upon the result of the evaluation of the main `<expression>`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If `<expression>` evaluates to `true`, then `<trueExpression>` will be evaluated, otherwise `<falseExpression>` is evaluated.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The result of the ternary operator does not have a rational number type, even if all of its operands are rational number literals.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The result type is determined from the types of the two operands in the same way as above, converting to their mobile type first if required.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] 1 : 0)` will revert due to arithmetic overflow.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] 1 : 0)` is of `uint8` type, which forces the addition to be performed in `uint8` as well, and 256 exceeds the range allowed for this type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Another consequence is that an expression like `1.5 + 1.5` is valid but `1.5 + (true ?
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This is because the former is a rational expression evaluated in unlimited precision and only its final value matters.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The latter involves a conversion of a fractional rational number to an integer, which is currently disallowed.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `a++` and `a--` are equivalent to `a += 1` / `a -= 1` but the expression itself still has the previous value of `a`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In contrast, `--a` and `++a` have the same effect on `a` but return the value after the change.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `delete a` assigns the initial value for the type to `a`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] I.e. for integers it is equivalent to `a = 0`, but it can also be used on arrays, where it assigns a dynamic array of length zero or a static array of the same length with all elements set to their initial value.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `delete a[x]` deletes the item at index `x` of the array and leaves all other elements and the length of the array untouched.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This especially means that it leaves a gap in the array.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If you plan to remove items, a mapping is probably a better choice.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] For structs, it assigns a struct with all members reset.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `delete` has no effect on mappings (as the keys of mappings may be arbitrary and are generally unknown).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] So if you delete a struct, it will reset all members that are not mappings and also recurse into the members unless they are mappings.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] However, individual keys and what they map to can be deleted: If `a` is a mapping, then `delete a[x]` will delete the value stored at `x`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] It is important to note that `delete a` really behaves like an assignment to `a`, i.e. it stores a new object in `a`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This distinction is visible when `a` is reference variable: It will only reset `a` itself, not the value it referred to previously.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The following is the order of precedence for operators, listed in order of evaluation.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] An implicit type conversion is automatically applied by the compiler in some cases during assignments, when passing arguments to functions and when applying operators.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In general, an implicit conversion between value-types is possible if it makes sense semantically and no information is lost.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] For example, `uint8` is convertible to `uint16` and `int128` to `int256`, but `int8` is not convertible to `uint256`, because `uint256` cannot hold values such as `-1`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If an operator is applied to different types, the compiler tries to implicitly convert one of the operands to the type of the other (the same is true for assignments).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This means that operations are always performed in the type of one of the operands.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] For more details about which implicit conversions are possible, please consult the sections about the types themselves.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In the example below, `y` and `z`, the operands of the addition, do not have the same type, but `uint8` can be implicitly converted to `uint16` and not vice-versa.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Because of that, `y` is converted to the type of `z` before the addition is performed in the `uint16` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] The resulting type of the expression `y + z` is `uint16`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Because it is assigned to a variable of type `uint32` another implicit conversion is performed after the addition.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If the compiler does not allow implicit conversion but you are confident a conversion will work, an explicit type conversion is sometimes possible.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] This may result in unexpected behavior and allows you to bypass some security features of the compiler, so be sure to test that the result is what you want and expect!
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] At the end of this code snippet, `x` will have the value `0xfffff..fd` (64 hex characters), which is -3 in the two’s complement representation of 256 bits.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If an integer is explicitly converted to a larger type, it is padded on the left (i.e., at the higher order end).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Fixed-size bytes types behave differently during conversions.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If a fixed-size bytes type is explicitly converted to a larger type, it is padded on the right.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] Since integers and fixed-size byte arrays behave differently when truncating or padding, explicit conversions between integers and fixed-size byte arrays are only allowed, if both have the same size.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] `bytes` arrays and `bytes` calldata slices can be converted explicitly to fixed bytes types (`bytes1`/…/`bytes32`).
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] In case the array is longer than the target fixed bytes type, truncation at the end will happen.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p02] If the array is shorter than the target type, it will be padded with zeros at the end.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] Prior to version 0.8.0, any decimal or hexadecimal number literals could be explicitly converted to an integer type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] From 0.8.0, such explicit conversions are as strict as implicit conversions, i.e., they are only allowed if the literal fits in the resulting range.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] Decimal number literals cannot be implicitly converted to fixed-size byte arrays.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] Hexadecimal number literals can be, but only if the number of hex digits exactly fits the size of the bytes type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] As described in Address Literals, hex literals of the correct size that pass the checksum test are of `address` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] No other literals can be implicitly converted to the `address` type.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] Explicit conversions to `address` are allowed only from `bytes20` and `uint160`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] An `address a` can be converted explicitly to `address payable` via `payable(a)`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] Prior to version 0.8.0, it was possible to explicitly convert from any integer type (of any size, signed or unsigned) to `address` or `address payable`.
[src:solidity-lang/latest-types-p03] Starting with 0.8.0 only conversion from `uint160` is allowed.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:solidity-lang/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The following contract is quite complex, but showcases a lot of Solidity’s features.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Of course, the main problems of electronic voting is how to assign voting rights to the correct persons and how to prevent manipulation.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] We will not solve all problems here, but at least we will show how delegated voting can be done so that vote counting is **automatic and completely transparent** at the same time.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The idea is to create one contract per ballot, providing a short name for each option.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Then the creator of the contract who serves as chairperson will give the right to vote to each address individually.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The persons behind the addresses can then choose to either vote themselves or to delegate their vote to a person they trust.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] At the end of the voting time, `winningProposal()` will return the proposal with the largest number of votes.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Currently, many transactions are needed to assign the rights to vote to all participants.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Moreover, if two or more proposals have the same number of votes, `winningProposal()` is not able to register a tie.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Can you think of a way to fix these issues?
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] In this section, we will show how easy it is to create a completely blind auction contract on Ethereum.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] We will start with an open auction where everyone can see the bids that are made and then extend this contract into a blind auction where it is not possible to see the actual bid until the bidding period ends.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The general idea of the following simple auction contract is that everyone can send their bids during a bidding period.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The bids already include sending some compensation, e.g.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Ether, in order to bind the bidders to their bid.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] If the highest bid is raised, the previous highest bidder gets their Ether back.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] After the end of the bidding period, the contract has to be called manually for the beneficiary to receive their Ether - contracts cannot activate themselves.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The previous open auction is extended to a blind auction in the following.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The advantage of a blind auction is that there is no time pressure towards the end of the bidding period.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Creating a blind auction on a transparent computing platform might sound like a contradiction, but cryptography comes to the rescue.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] During the **bidding period**, a bidder does not actually send their bid, but only a hashed version of it.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Since it is currently considered practically impossible to find two (sufficiently long) values whose hash values are equal, the bidder commits to the bid by that.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] After the end of the bidding period, the bidders have to reveal their bids: They send their values unencrypted, and the contract checks that the hash value is the same as the one provided during the bidding period.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Another challenge is how to make the auction **binding and blind** at the same time: The only way to prevent the bidder from just not sending the Ether after they won the auction is to make them send it together with the bid.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Since value transfers cannot be blinded in Ethereum, anyone can see the value.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The following contract solves this problem by accepting any value that is larger than the highest bid.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Since this can of course only be checked during the reveal phase, some bids might be **invalid**, and this is on purpose (it even provides an explicit flag to place invalid bids with high-value transfers): Bidders can confuse competition by placing several high or low invalid bids.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Purchasing goods remotely currently requires multiple parties that need to trust each other.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The simplest configuration involves a seller and a buyer.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The buyer would like to receive an item from the seller and the seller would like to get some compensation, e.g.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The problematic part is the shipment here: There is no way to determine for sure that the item arrived at the buyer.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] There are multiple ways to solve this problem, but all fall short in one or the other way.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] In the following example, both parties have to put twice the value of the item into the contract as escrow.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] As soon as this happened, the Ether will stay locked inside the contract until the buyer confirms that they received the item.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] After that, the buyer is returned the value (half of their deposit) and the seller gets three times the value (their deposit plus the value).
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The idea behind this is that both parties have an incentive to resolve the situation or otherwise their Ether is locked forever.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] This contract of course does not solve the problem, but gives an overview of how you can use state machine-like constructs inside a contract.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] In this section, we will learn how to build an example implementation of a payment channel.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] It uses cryptographic signatures to make repeated transfers of Ether between the same parties secure, instantaneous, and without transaction fees.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] For the example, we need to understand how to sign and verify signatures, and setup the payment channel.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Imagine Alice wants to send some Ether to Bob, i.e.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Alice is the sender and Bob is the recipient.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Alice only needs to send cryptographically signed messages off-chain (e.g. via email) to Bob and it is similar to writing checks.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Alice and Bob use signatures to authorize transactions, which is possible with smart contracts on Ethereum.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Alice will build a simple smart contract that lets her transmit Ether, but instead of calling a function herself to initiate a payment, she will let Bob do that, and therefore pay the transaction fee.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Alice does not need to interact with the Ethereum network to sign the transaction, the process is completely offline.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] In this tutorial, we will sign messages in the browser using web3.js and MetaMask, using the method described in EIP-712, as it provides a number of other security benefits.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The `web3.eth.personal.sign` prepends the length of the message to the signed data.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Since we hash first, the message will always be exactly 32 bytes long, and thus this length prefix is always the same.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] A replay attack is when a signed message is reused to claim authorization for a second action.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] To avoid replay attacks we use the same technique as in Ethereum transactions themselves, a so-called nonce, which is the number of transactions sent by an account.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] The smart contract checks if a nonce is used multiple times.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Another type of replay attack can occur when the owner deploys a `ReceiverPays` smart contract, makes some payments, and then destroys the contract.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Later, they decide to deploy the `RecipientPays` smart contract again, but the new contract does not know the nonces used in the previous deployment, so the attacker can use the old messages again.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Alice can protect against this attack by including the contract’s address in the message, and only messages containing the contract’s address itself will be accepted.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] You can find an example of this in the first two lines of the `claimPayment()` function of the full contract at the end of this section.
[src:solidity-lang/solidity-by-example] Furthermore, instead of destroying the contract by calling `selfdestruct`, which is currently deprecated, we will disable the contract’s functionalities by freezing it, resulting in the reversion of any call after it being frozen.
